      <description>Yeast infection in mouth is commonly cause by the yeast strain Candida. Candida normally exists in the digestive tract and the vagina in a regulated amount.   It  often affects babies and the elderly or geriatrics.
The cause of this infection starts from invasion of the tissues, making you hypersensitive. There are four types of oral candidiasis: [...]&lt;br&gt;&lt;a type="audio/mpeg" href="http://podcasts.odiogo.com/get_mp3.mp3?f=/yeast-infection-relief-blog/Yeast_Infection_Relief_Blog-What_You_Need_to_Know_about_Oral_Yeast_Infection.mp3"&gt;Click here to play&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;</description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" align="justify"><strong>Yeast infection in mouth</strong> is commonly cause by the yeast strain Candida. <a href="http://www.yeastinfectionreliefblog.com/yeast-infection-relief/intestinal-candida/" target="_blank">Candida </a>normally exists in the digestive tract and the vagina in a regulated amount.   It  often affects babies and the elderly or geriatrics.</p>
<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" align="justify">The cause of this infection starts from invasion of the tissues, making you hypersensitive. There are four types of oral candidiasis: Moniliasis or thrush is a white or yellow film covering the tongue and insides of the mouth; when wiped, a reddish tissue underneath is seen.</p>
<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" align="justify">Erythematous is red patches that peel and seen on the palate or on the tongue. Hyperplastic is the chronic state of oral yeast infection, it is when it cannot be removed or wiped because it is stained by food fragments or by smoking. Angular cheilitis are reddish cracks or fissures at the mouth corners. Symptoms are painful and burning sensation, although some report to have no such symptoms at all.</p>
<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" align="justify">Other report, they experience unusual craving for sugar, bread, alcohol; some experience depression and muscle pains. <strong><a href="http://www.yeastinfectionreliefblog.com/yeastinfectionomore" target="_blank">Yeast infection</a> </strong>in mouth<strong> </strong>is treated with antifungal antibiotics like Nystatin.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
