<p><small><a title="Attribution License" href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.yeastinfectionreliefblog.com/wp-content/plugins/photo-dropper/images/cc.png" border="0" alt="Creative Commons License" width="16" height="16" align="absmiddle" /></a> <a href="http://www.photodropper.com/photos/" target="_blank">photo</a> credit: <a title="FLOODkOFF" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/15560644@N03/3709959426/" target="_blank">FLOODkOFF</a></small> A <strong>yeast infection diet</strong> includes removing the kinds of food that <a href="http://www.yeastinfectionreliefblog.com/yeast-infection-relief/yeast-infection-causes/" target="_blank">yeast </a>thrives on. An example is sugar which is full of empty calories. Sugar increases the level of blood sugar once it is released into the bloodstream. Consume foods that are considered pro and prebiotics.</p>
<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" align="justify">These are considered as good bacteria that keeps your immune system regulated. Examples of these are yogurts. There are also probiotic capsules available for you if you&#8217;d like to take a higher dose. Prebiotics on the other hand are indigested carbohydrates which fight off yeast.</p>
<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" align="justify">Examples of these are oatmeal, wheat that&#8217;s unprocessed, barley and soybeans.</p>
